the problem with professional networking

Opening LinkedIn feels like walking into a job fair
in your own living room.

what's broken

Your profile is a frozen résumé pretending to be a living person.

LinkedIn was built in 2003 when your employer was your identity. It hasn't changed. Connecting feels like cold outreach at a job fair. Creating content feels like writing a TED talk for a crowd that will judge you. And the people doing the most interesting work are the ones least visible on it.

01
Entirely backwards-looking
Your profile is history. No signal of where you are right now.
02
Connection = cold outreach
No natural entry point. Every intro requires a cover letter.
03
The feed is a performance stage
Nobody wants to perform every day. Most say nothing.
04
Freelancers, builders, in-betweeners: invisible
The model fails everyone without a clean employment line.
where net fits

The gap between Twitter and LinkedIn.

Twitter has thinking with no professional depth. LinkedIn has depth with no thinking. NET is both — and neither.

Twitter / X
Thinking happening. Professional context missing.
LinkedIn
Professional depth. But thinking replaced by performance.
net.
What you're working on right now. Who's thinking the same thing nearby. No performance required.
the metaphor

Your network is a rope. Not a graph.

A graph is cold. Nodes and edges. Points connected by lines. A rope has texture, tension, temperature. It has memory. It frays. It knots in places where it was tied to something real.

01
Your rope has temperature
Connections are TENSION (active), COOLING (drifting), or DORMANT (faded). Not a number — a state.
02
Knots form at real moments
When you slot someone's card, a knot forms. Not a follow — a record of why, when, and what thread you were both pulling.
03
The rack holds your world
A curtain rail runs across the top of your screen. Cards hang from it. Your network is visible, editable, alive.
04
Serendipity, not algorithm
NET connects by momentum — not history. Not "you both worked in tech" but "you're both pulling on the same thread right now."
three screens. that's it.

Simple enough to use at a coffee shop.
Powerful enough to change who you meet.

01 · worlds
Your feed is a deck, not a river.

One card at a time. Scroll deliberately. Slot a card onto your rope — a knot forms. No algorithm decides what matters. Resonance with your current thought does.

The more diverse your knots, the richer your rope. Not more followers — more dimensions of thinking, more fields crossing, more unexpected doors.

the card

Not a post. A signal.

The card is a snapshot of your current state. Not finished thinking. Thinking happening now. One photo, one line. That's enough to start a real conversation.

Slot hole — top right
Empty = not on your rope. Tap to slot — this forms a knot. A haptic click. The beginning of a connection without sending a single message.
The thought — one line
The question, problem, or hypothesis you're holding right now. Not a headline. Not a caption. The actual thing on your mind.
Sticker strip — face stack
Each face = someone who attached a thought to this card. Tap a face to open their sticker and its thread. A public layer of sideways thinking.
Flip the card
Tap the photo to reveal the back: why now, what threads, what kind of connection you're open to. The back is the whole point.
Bridge me
Don't ask them to connect you. Ask them to open a door. The serendipity gesture — for introductions that couldn't have been planned.
